input: What is the sport called Cricket
label: Cricket is a sport first originated in Wngland. Cricket was invented by British. While cricket was primarily played starting 17th century, there have been some obscure and speculative references of sport being played in 13th century during era of King Edward II. Cricket is game played with a flat bat and a ball with each team consisting of 11 players. The goal of the game is to score as many runs as a team can score while getting their turn to bat and getting the other team out before they can reach their target. Each team can bat once and have to field while other team bats. Cricket is played in circular or oval shaped fields. The patch in the middle of the ground is called the pitch which is 22 yards in length. At each end of the pitch, three sticks are planted in the ground called stumps. Two small wooden pieces are placed on top of stumps called bails. This setup is called a wicket. Two batters from the batting team will bat on each end of the pitch. Runs are scored by hitting a ball and then running back and forth from one end of the pitch to another end. Batter can send the ball to the boundary while pitching on the ground one or more times

Often enterprises need help when a business user and technical expert try to define a business use case.  A technical expert, in-house or vendor, considers it an engineering problem, while a business user needs it to have a business impact.  Multiple frameworks can help build consensus.  However, an ideal approach will go through these steps.
1. Identify a business outcome.  This is a very high-level outcome that is industry aligned and has no technical description.  An example from the healthcare industry is a 'better patient experience.'
2. List strategies defined by an organisation to deliver these outcomes.  To our example in step 1, one approach is reducing patient wait time when attending a hospital.'
3. Clarify the KPIs and measurements listed in these strategies.  In this example, it can be 'Max patient wait time of 20 mins'. 
4. List business capabilities that can deliver results towards these KPIs.  Here we can think of ways patients can register their details electronically on their own or hospital devices vs paper forms.  Each entry will initiate an automated process to assign the right staff and resources to address patient needs.

input: Where is Rakaia Gorge located?
output:
MapsRakaia Gorge is located at the south-west end of The Gorge, just east of the junction of Main North Road and Flowerdale-Marlborough Road.

Is there a pool or spa near Rakaia Gorge?
Yes, there is a swimming pool and spa in the centre of Rakaia, with a children's pool for the kids.

Is there a forest service campground near Rakaia Gorge?
Sure, you will find a Forest Service campground at the Rakaia Gorge Visitor Centre.

Are there any other tourist facilities in Rakaia?
There is a licensed café/bar/restaurant in the centre of Rakaia, and a small caravan park in the town itself.

How can I get to Rakaia Gorge?
Rakaia Gorge is located at the south-west end of The Gorge, just east of the junction of Main North Road and Flowerdale-Marlborough Road. The visitor centre is situated on the Main North Road, a couple of kilometres south of the junction of Main North Road and Flowerdale-Marlborough Road.

How long is the Gorge?
The Gorge is approximately 7 km long and up to 550 m wide. It is a spectacular gorge, with steep cliffs on either side, and a number of waterfalls.

What is the best way to see the gorge?
The best way to see the Gorge is to walk or drive the main part of the gorge, and stop off at the viewpoints along the way.

Is there a road to Rakaia Gorge?
There is a 5.5 km gravel road north of the visitor centre, which leads up to the top of the gorge. This road is closed in both directions on Sundays.

What is the weather like in Rakaia?
The area is relatively dry and when the wind blows, it can be quite cold during the summer months.

What time of year is best to visit Rakaia Gorge?
During the warmer months (September and October), it is possible to walk from the visitor centre to the top of the gorge. If it is windy, it can be quite cold on a walk up the gorge, so it is best to wear a jacket.

Do I need a camping permit?
Yes, a camping permit is required to camp within the Rakaia G

* automation
* compliance documentation
* business process improvement
* standardization

The Sydney Opera House is a multi-venue performing arts centre in Sydney. Located on the foreshore of Sydney Harbour, it is widely regarded as one of the world's most famous and distinctive buildings and a masterpiece of 20th-century architecture.

Designed by Danish architect Jorn Utzon, but completed by an Australian architectural team headed by Peter Hall, the building was formally opened by Queen Elizabeth II on 20 October 1973 after a gestation beginning with Utzon's 1957 selection as winner of an international design competition. The Government of New South Wales, led by the premier, Joseph Cahill, authorised work to begin in 1958 with Utzon directing construction. The government's decision to build Utzon's design is often overshadowed by circumstances that followed, including cost and scheduling overruns as well as the architect's ultimate resignation.

The building and its surrounds occupy the whole of Bennelong Point on Sydney Harbour, between Sydney Cove and Farm Cove, adjacent to the Sydney central business district and the Royal Botanic Gardens, and near to the Sydney Harbour Bridge.

Continuous Integration means that both teams practice Continuous Integration, which means that the code is checked in to version control very frequently. This speeds up the process of producing quality software by preventing regressions and detecting bugs faster.

Continuous Deployment means that both teams practice Continuous Deployment, which means that the code is almost continuously deployed to production. This ensures that the software is secure as soon as it is released, and makes it easier to rollback changes if they are found to be insecure.

Continuous Testing means that both teams practice Continuous Testing, which means that the software is constantly tested for security and quality. This makes it possible to detect and fix bugs faster, and ensures that the software is secure when it is released to production.

Continuous Monitoring means that both teams practice Continuous Monitoring, which means that the software is constantly monitored for security vulnerabilities. This makes it possible to quickly fix security vulnerabilities before they can cause problems.

The DevSecOps approach is based on the YAGNI principle, which means "you aren't going to need it".

This means that security flaws that are found in the software are fixed before they become serious security problems. This reduces the time and effort that is needed to create secure software.

How is DevSecOps different from Continuous Integration, Continuous Deployment, Continuous Testing, and Continuous Monitoring?

Continuous Integration, Continuous Deployment, Continuous Testing, and Continuous Monitoring are all different types of Continuous Integration, and all these methods are used together to ensure that the software is secure before it is released to production.

However, these methods are not the same.

For example, Continuous Integration is a continuous integration method, which means that it is a method that is practiced by both the software development and the security teams.

However, Continuous Deployment is a continuous deployment method, which means that it is a method that is practiced by only the software development team.

DevSecOps is a more integrated approach
label: DevSecOps is an augmentation of DevOps with security integrated into the DevOps approach. It has been growing in recent years as producing secure software is becoming a top priority for companies.

I'd say Rhapsody, Tales of the Abyss, and Knights in the Nightmare are all great examples of great Japanese RPGs.

Rhapsody is a great example of a turn based RPG, where you progress through the game. It has a lot of interesting characters, and the story is pretty good. Rhapsody is one of the only games that I can say has really captured my attention for the past 8 years.

Tales of the Abyss is another good example. It's a little more of a hack and slash RPG, and has a lot of interesting characters. The story is a little better than Rhapsody, but not by much.

Knights in the Nightmare is a more traditional RPG, and tells the story of a young man who is involved in a war against a race known as the Nephilim. It's a great story, and there are a lot of cool characters in this game.

I'd say that you should try out Tales of Symphonia, which is a great example of a hack and slash RPG. It's pretty much the same style as Tales of the Abyss, but it has a lot more characters in it.

The normal combat in Xenoblade is still the same, but you can switch between two characters to control different parts of the story. And the story is pretty good, and the characters are interesting.

In a nutshell, the Pareto principle is a law of nature that states that 80% of the effects come from 20% of the causes. The 20% of the causes are also called top-N causes.
A very important detail is that this is not a law about what is the largest value of a variable. The Pareto principle only applies to distributions of variables, and not to distributions of values.
Essentially, if you have a variable $X$, you can find the top-N causes of the variable $X$ by finding the set of all the causes $C$ which contribute more than 80% of the total effect of $X$ on the observed variable $Y$.
For example, if you have a variable $X$ with a normal distribution, then the Pareto principle can be applied to it by finding the set of all the causes $C$ which contribute more than 80% of the total effect of $X$ on the observed variable $Y$.

]]>Cats are masters of the art of thermoregulation, able to regulate their own temperature better than humans and most other animals. You may have noticed that cats have fur, and they can also sweat. What is the difference between the two? The main difference is the amount of water that is lost.

Cats have very little sweat glands. They are able to regulate their temperature by moving the water between the skin and the environment. The amount of water that is lost through the skin is very small compared to the amount of water lost through the lungs. Cats are very good at regulating their body temperature, and they are able to regulate their temperature quickly. Humans can lose about 7% of their body weight in sweat every day, and we have a much larger surface area to lose water through.

The short answer is “because they are cats.” That being said, it is interesting to note that dogs are also capable of thermoregulation, but they are not as good at it as cats are. They do not have as much fur to lose water through, and they do not have the same ability to regulate their body temperature as cats do. This is why they can get heat exhaustion easily. Dogs who are unable to regulate their body temperature properly will have a very high risk of heat stroke.

The question is not whether or not a chocolate is a chocolate. It is whether or not a chocolate is a 'chocolate'.
A chocolate is defined by the specific type of chocolate (class) and the specific brand of chocolate (subclass). In this case there are many different types of chocolate, all of which are defined by their specific type (class) and their specific brand (subclass). The specific subclasses may be listed in the question, but the specific brand (and thus the specific class) is not.

I think that the question could be rephrased as "Which of the following is a chocolate?" I think that the answer would be "It depends on the brand and the flavor".  
For example, if I allowed 0.5% cocoa, but not dark, then Twix would not be a chocolate.  If I allowed dark, but not dark-chocolate, then Twix would not be a chocolate.  If I allowed dark-chocolate (say, a Melanie's), then Twix would be a chocolate.  If I allowed dark-chocolate (say, a Callebaut), then Twix would not be a chocolate.

But as long as the ingredients are the same, it seems to me that the question is logically equivalent, and answers the same way.
In the other direction, if I allowed 0.5% cocoa and dark, then Twix would not be a chocolate.  If I allowed dark-chocolate, then Twix would not be a chocolate.  So, I think that the answer to the question is "yes".

input: Write a summary of the outdoor activities to do in Colorado
output:
Write a summary of the outdoor activities to do in Colorado

Adventure Expedition

The best way to explore the Colorado Rockies is on foot, and we have the right tour to suit every level of experience. Start your adventure trek with a one day trip to the majestic Rocky Mountain National Park, with its impressive peaks, lush forests and wildlife. The park offers many trails for hikers to explore, and most are short and scenic enough to be completed in a day.

You can learn more about the park and its history on a guided tour through the main entrance to the park. Many of the park’s trails are open to the public, but you can also choose to explore the backcountry on a guided tour, which offers the additional benefit of the park rangers’ guidance. The park is home to elk, mountain goats, deer, raptors and many other species of wildlife. The park is best known for its wildlife, but it also offers decent hiking, mountain biking and horseback riding.

The afternoon is yours to explore the park at your own pace. Park rangers can also provide information about the park’s flora and fauna, and the geology of the park and its surrounding areas.

After a full day of exploring the park, or if you just want to relax in the park, you can also choose to stay in the village of Estes Park, which offers a variety of accommodations and outdoor activities.

If you are looking for a slightly more challenging hiking experience, you can chose the Colorado Trail. The Colorado Trail is a high-elevation hiking trail that is about 42 miles long, and it runs along the Continental Divide. The trail is very popular with hikers and is maintained by the Colorado Trail Association. The trail is not accessible year-round, but it is best to plan your trip during spring and fall.

The Colorado Trail is only open to hikers, but you can also choose to hike the Cherry Creek, Roaring Fork or Ouray Trails, which are shorter and more manageable for shorter treks.

The trails are maintained by the Colorado Trail Association, and you can get information about the trail and trail conditions from the association. The association offers a variety of guided hikes for all experience levels.

Another great option for hiking in Colorado is to visit the town of Gunnison, which is located in the northeastern part of the state. The town offers a variety of outdoor activities
label: There are many outdoor activities that you can do in Colorado year around. It is best to determine whether you want to participate in those activities during summer or winter. For summer outdoor activities, there are adventurous activities like hiking, mountain biking, whitewater rafting and fly-fishing. There are also many outdoor activities in the winter like downhill skiing, cross-country skiing, snowboarding, snowshoeing and snowmobiling. Regardless of the time of year, there are many outdoor activities that you can do in Colorado.

label:
Lia Cirio is an American ballet dancer. She is a principal dancer at Boston Ballet. 

Cirio is half Filipino. She trained at Swarthmore Ballet Theatre and Central Pennsylvania Youth Ballet. At age 16, she joined Boston Ballet II. She joined the main company's corps de ballet in 2004, at age 16, and was the company's Princess Grace Award nominee the same year. Cirio was named second soloist in 2006 and soloist the following year. In 2008 and 2009, Cirio joined the Trey McIntyre Project, and toured with the company in the United States and the world. She returned to Boston Ballet in the 2009-10 season and was promoted to principal in 2010. She has danced roles such as Odette/Odile in Swan Lake and the title role in Cinderella.

Cirio has also choreographed work for Boston Ballet's ChoreograpHER initiative.

Cirio is the older sister of Jeffrey Cirio, a Lead Principal Dancer at English National Ballet. They have established an artistic collective called Cirio Collective in 2015.

From the given text, list the movies of Shah Rukh Khan in a chronological manner.

You are supposed to match each movie with its release date and predict the next movie to be released.

Example

Code:

Release Date: 2018

Next Movie: 2019

Solution

Code:

import datetime

def next_movie(movie_text, release_date):

release_dict = []

for line in movie_text.splitlines():

line = line.strip()

if line.startswith('Release Date:'):

line = line.replace('Release Date:', '')

release_date = line.split(':')[1]

release_dict.append(release_date)

start_date = datetime.datetime.strptime(release_date, '%Y %m %d')

for date in release_dict:

if date > start_date:

next_movie(movie_text, date)

return next_movie(movie_text, release_date)

The present invention relates to a method of manufacturing a semiconductor device, and more particularly to a semiconductor device manufacturing method, that can prevent an oxide film from being peeled off from a side wall of a trench.
As the semiconductor industry has developed in recent years, the size of a transistor has been continuously reduced. As the size of a transistor is reduced, the width of a channel region is also reduced. As the width of a channel region is reduced, a short channel effect is generated. The short channel effect causes problems such as drain induced barrier lowering (DIBL), hot carrier effect, and the like.
To solve these problems, a salicide (self-aligned silicide) process has been proposed. The salicide process reduces the width of a channel region and thereby suppresses the short channel effect.
The salicide process is a process in which, when a gate electrode and a source/drain region are formed, a metal is deposited on a substrate including the gate electrode and the source/drain region by using a salicide process.
The salicide process forms a metal silicide layer having a low resistivity on a surface of a semiconductor substrate, and thereby limits the resistance of the source/drain region and the gate electrode.

Growing up in Medellin, Colombia, Romain Iannetta was a star in the making. He was a talented boxer that would eventually play in the NBA with the Utah Jazz, but that wasn't his first basketball team. In a 2005 D-League All-Star Game against the NBA's Los Angeles Clippers, Iannetta scored a career-high 25 points to help the Washington Wizards take down the Clippers.

He would go on to play for the Wizards from 2005 to 2007 and then the Los Angeles Clippers in 2008-09. In his time with the Wizards, he averaged 7.8 points and 1.2 rebounds in 34 games. He would also play with the Milwaukee Bucks, Dallas Mavericks, Los Angeles Lakers and Charlotte Hornets.

specific layer.)

In the end, I suspect that the semantic layer is just a convenient term for
the presentation layer.

------
marcamillion
I actually like this idea...I might have to try it myself.

But you know what I don't like?

The fact that the term 'Semantic Layer' is not widely used. I mean it's not a
bad term, but it's not a great term. And it gets me thinking that maybe we
should be using something else.

I know that Google does not use the term...but I think they are the only
software company that does. So maybe it's a good idea to use something else.

I think the term 'Model' is a pretty good one, but I am not sure if it is
widely used.

Personally, I like the term 'Domain Model'.

So, question: If/when
label: A Semantic Layer provides a friendly abstraction to data such that users can get trustworthy answers from data without an understanding of its technical representation.

input: What is a good way to convince someone to do something
output:
the same way as the previous person?

Problem: We received an e-mail from a person who has been very helpful in the past. The e-mail said only the following:

"I am writing to report that I have done as you asked me to do. I have clearly stated that I would do this and I will follow through. I hope that this report will be the third in a series of reports that will confirm that I have been a valuable asset to your organization."

We know from experience that these types of "promises" are not worth much. What should we do in this situation?

Solution: The first step is to contact the person and request some specific information. For example, "What did you do to ensure that you would do what I asked you to do?" and "Did you follow up to make sure that you did what I asked you to do?"

Second, it is important to ask for a "warrant." The warrant is a promise to do the action specified in the "report." The warrant will show that the person has the ability to follow through with the action.

Third, make sure that you have a plan to contact the person in the future if the person doesn't follow through on the action. This will enable you to monitor the situation and take appropriate action.

Fourth, be sure that the person really means what he or she says. If you are not convinced, then do not take the person's word for it.

Fifth, be sure that the person is not trying to take advantage of you.

Sixth, be sure that you follow the proper procedures when taking action. For example, if a person makes a promise to do something, then the person should be in a position to do it if the person doesn't follow through on the promise.

Seventh, be sure that the person is not trying to find a way to make you feel bad about taking action against them. For example, it is better to ask "Is this something you can do?" than to say "You didn't do what you promised to do. Now what are you going to do?"

A common problem that most people have has to do with discretion. Suppose that a person tells you, "I am going to take care of it for you. I will take care of it for you." What is the problem with this?

3) Use the personal rapport that you have built with the person to convince them
4) Explain how your counterpart will personally benefit from taking the action
5) Help the person understand that the action is easy, quick or low effort
6) Propose an exchange, where you do something in the interest of the person in exchange for their action
7) Pay the person for taking the action
Depending on their personality, the action, and your relationship with the person different methods may work better.

input: What do you get by substituting the oxygen in the isocyanate group with a sulfur?
output:
.

The answer is a diphenylmethane diisocyanate.

The compound is so strong it can be used in place of the methylene diphenyl di isocyanate (MDI) that's otherwise used to make polyurethanes.

"The advantage of this reaction is that it gives you a very tough polyurethane, which is a very useful polymer," said Toshio Kurita, a chemist at Nihon University in Japan.

The reaction is likely to be used commercially in the near future, Kurita said.

The discovery was reported online in the current issue of the Journal of Organic Chemistry.

(Editor's note: Paul Laudon is a science writer based in New York. His work has appeared in The Washington Post, The New York Times, and The Los Angeles Times, among other publications.)

Copyright 2014 NPR. To see more, visit http://www.npr.org/.

Transcript

ROBERT SIEGEL, HOST:

The chemical industry is in the midst of a revolution. The key to this revolution is a chemical reaction. It's the chance to use a powerful chemical, a molecule containing sulfur, instead of one containing oxygen.

NPR science correspondent Paul Laudon has been reporting on this chemical reaction, and we're going to hear about it in a minute. But first, we wanted to learn more about the reaction itself. So I called Toshio Kurita, a chemist at Nihon University in Japan.

TOSHIO KURITA: The reaction is very easy to do.

SIEGEL: What do you do?

KURITA: You take a compound containing two primary amines, and you add hydrogen cyanide.

SIEGEL: Hydrogen cyanide?

KURITA: Hydrogen cyanide is a very strong base.

SIEGEL: You're talking about potassium cyanide?

KURITA: We used potassium cyanide. It gives you a very tough polyurethane, which is a very useful polymer.

SIEGEL: So you have a two-step process. First, you make the compound containing the two primary amines. Then you use a strong acid to remove the hydrogen cyanide.

KURITA: Yes.

SIEGEL: So tell me - tell me what has happened to the hydrogen cyanide
label:
In organic chemistry, isothiocyanate is the functional group −N=C=S, formed by substituting the oxygen in the isocyanate group with a sulfur. Many natural isothiocyanates from plants are produced by enzymatic conversion of metabolites called glucosinolates. These natural isothiocyanates, such as allyl isothiocyanate, are also known as mustard oils. An artificial isothiocyanate, phenyl isothiocyanate, is used for amino acid sequencing in the Edman degradation.

Cruciferous vegetables, such as bok choy, broccoli, cabbage, cauliflower, kale, and others, are rich sources of glucosinolate precursors of isothiocyanates. Although there has been some basic research on how isothiocyanates might exert biological effects in vivo, there is no high-quality evidence to date for its efficacy against human diseases

The present invention relates to the field of liquid crystal display devices, and in particular, to a liquid crystal display device and the driving method thereof.
2. The Prior Arts
Liquid crystal display (LCD) devices have been widely used as display devices in various electronic products, such as notebook computers and personal digital assistants (PDAs). In most liquid crystal display devices, a liquid crystal panel is provided for displaying images, wherein the liquid crystal panel includes a plurality of pixel electrodes and a plurality of thin film transistors (TFTs) respectively at the four corners of the liquid crystal panel, and a storage capacitor.
The pixel electrodes are arranged in an array form, and the TFTs are arranged in an array form to control the transmission of the pixel signals to the pixel electrodes. The storage capacitor is utilized to store the pixel signals, and the pixel signals are transmitted to the pixel electrodes via the TFTs. The liquid crystal molecules of the liquid crystal panel have an anisotropic property and are controlled by the electric field between the pixel electrodes and the common electrode. The liquid crystal molecules are controlled to change the transmittance of the light, thereby displaying the image.
However, the pixel electrodes and the TFTs are arranged in an array form on the liquid crystal panel, and a red, green and blue color filter is arranged on the liquid crystal panel for displaying color images. Thus, the aperture ratio of the liquid crystal panel is low, and the light luminance of the liquid crystal panel is reduced.
In addition, the pixel electrodes are driven by the gate lines to transmit the pixel signals, and the TFTs are driven by the data lines to transmit the pixel signals. The gate lines and the data lines are arranged in an array form on the liquid crystal panel, and the cross point of the gate lines and the data lines defines a pixel region. 1. Democrats and progressives believed the income tax to be fairer method of generating revenue than tariffs (taxes on the import and export of goods).
2. Western and southern states were concerned about commodity prices, which were impacted by tariffs, and therefore preferred an alternative means of revenue.
3. Republicans were split on whether to oppose or support amendment.

input: What is OAuth 2.0?
output:
is a protocol for exchanging authorization information between a user and a server. It is based on the OAuth 1.0a specification.

How does OAuth 2.0 work? OAuth 2.0 uses client-side browser application code instead of a server-side scripting language such as PHP. The client-side application code serves as the server, and the user interacts with the application to get authorization and then send requests to the server.

Who is using OAuth 2.0? The protocol is being used in commercial products and not in more than 1 billion requests per day. Designers of software for managing passwords/accounts use OAuth 2.0.

OAuth 2.0 uses JSON as a data format.

What are the benefits of using OAuth 2.0? OAuth 2.0 is based on defined security standards.

OAuth 2.0 is faster than OAuth 1.0.

What are the differences between OAuth 2.0 and OAuth 1.0?

OAuth 2.0 is based on the OAuth 1.0a specification, which means client-side browser application code is involved as a server.

OAuth 2.0 stores information in a JSON format, while OAuth 1.0 stores information in the query string of the URL.

OAuth 2.0 provides an authorization code to the user. OAuth 2.0 does not provide an access token to the user. OAuth 2.0 also uses a separate parameter: scope to determine what information is included in the authorization code. In OAuth 1.0, the scope was the URL path.

What are the flow diagrams for OAuth 2.0? There are two flow diagrams for OAuth 2.0, depending on how the client requests an authorization code.

If the client requests an authorization code when it is authenticating itself to the server, the server gives the client an authorization code. The client then creates a token and authenticates with the token. The server then verifies the token. The client is redirected back to the authorization server, and the authorization server gives the client an access token. The client then uses the access token to access the protected resource.

If the client does not request an authorization code when it is authenticating itself to the server, the server gives the client an authorization code. The client then creates a token and authenticates with the token. The server then verifies
label: OAuth 2.0, which stands for “Open Authorization”, is a standard designed to allow a website or application to access resources hosted by other web apps on behalf of a user. It replaced OAuth 1.0 in 2012 and is now the de facto industry standard for online authorization.

I am a big fan of having a Goodwill in my town to go to for a variety of
things.

Yes, they are heavily saturated, and I know that the higher priced items are
sorted into the lower price categories, but there is still a lot of
interesting stuff that can be had for a lot less than the high end department
stores are selling for.

I can find a lot of stuff that I want at the Goodwill - from furniture to
electronics to big pieces of machinery - that I can't find elsewhere. Maybe
that is because I am not looking hard enough, but sometimes I do find awesome
things that I can't find elsewhere.

In the past I have found a lot of cool stuff, from a working 1980s video
game console to a busted 1980s Apple II.

I also find a lot of junk, and I can never go there without hoping that there
is a really good knock off or brand-name knock-off of something that I would
like to use in my home.

But I do love the fact that they stock a lot of unique products, from old
magazines to some unusual electronic equipment that I can't find anywhere
else.

------
aaronchall
I'm not sure if the concept of "Goodwill" is a good idea. I think most people
would be better served by a "Cash for Clothes" type of program.

I grew up in a small town in the midwest. For those who don't know, people
here don't have a lot of money. There are two big department store chains, and
they're both expensive.

We don't have a Walmart or Costco as such, but we do have a "big box" store
that's like a Walmart. I got my first job there, and I learned that the
clothes that I would have paid $5 for at the Goodwill are now on sale in
their "clearance" section for $5.50.

The only problem is that I have a small amount of clothing. I don't care to
buy used clothing, so I end up donating it.

The PEDALS method is a method of teaching patients with spinal cord injury how to use a handcycle to improve their independence and quality of life.

Why is PEDALS important?

PedALS helps a person with a spinal cord injury move and learn to use a handcycle. It can help improve an individual’s independence and quality of life. It can also help decrease the risk of secondary complications that can occur as mobility increases.

What is the PEDALS program?

The PEDALS program includes instruction from a certified PEDALS instructor. The instructor will teach you how to properly use your handcycle for a specified period of time. Each participant will learn how to cycle on a handcycle in the PEDALS program. The instructor will also assure proper fit of the handcycle for each individual.

What is the PEDALS method?

PEDALS is a method of teaching PALS participants how to independently operate their handcycle. To participate in PEDALS, the individual must be able to independently use their hands and arms to operate their handcycle.

What are the benefits of participating in PEDALS?

Improving Independence

Reducing the risk of secondary complications

Reducing the risk of joint stiffness

Improving the overall quality of life

Individuals with spinal cord injury who have been diagnosed with an acute cervical or thoracic injury as of the previous 12 months and who are able to independently use their hands and arms, or are able to independently operate a handcycle

Individuals with a chronic cervical or thoracic injury who are able to independently use their hands and arms

input: What happened on January 6, 2021?
output:
's Banner of Truth had been returned to him, and he had been shunted off to the side...

He'd heard it all before.

And he knew what was coming next.

"Well, that's twice I've saved your ass, J.D.," he said, settling into his seat. "I'll do it again."

"Don't think you'll be able to save me from myself, Rayner," J.D. said, staring straight ahead.

"How about if I just drive you to the airport and leave you there?"

"You want to let me out at the airport?"

"Sure," Rayner said. "Why not?"

J.D. took a deep breath. "Because I think I'm going to do something stupid."

"What kind of stupid?"

"I don't know. But I'm going to do it."

"What?"

"I'm going to have a drink."

"Okay."

"I'm going to have a drink and then I'm going to put my head on the table and cry for an hour."

"Okay."

"After that, I'm going to have a drink and then I'm going to buy a ticket for the next flight out of here. And I'm going to leave."

"Okay," Rayner said again.

"J.D.?"

"Yeah?"

"Thanks."

"You're welcome."

"Bye."

"Bye, John."

Rayner watched J.D. make his way to the bar, saw him unpack and set up in the small round table, saw him pour a glass of whiskey and lift it to his lips and drink.

And then he watched him heave his head forward and sob.

He felt a pang of regret. He should have known J.D. wasn't the type who could take a slight.

But J.D. had been through hell, and he was going to take his time getting through this, too.

He'd been there. He'd seen it.

And he'd done the best he could.

He could have sent J.D. home to his family, but instead he'd opted to keep him. Because he'd known that J.D., whom he loved, would help him.

On January 6, 2021, following the defeat of U.S. President Donald Trump in the 2020 presidential election, a mob of his supporters attacked the United States Capitol Building in Washington, D.C. The mob sought to keep Trump in power by preventing a joint session of Congress from counting the electoral college votes to formalize the victory of President-elect Joe Biden. According to the House select committee investigating the incident, the attack was the culmination of a seven-part plan by Trump to overturn the election. Five people died either shortly before, during, or following the event: one was shot by Capitol Police, another died of a drug overdose, and three died of natural causes. Many people were injured, including 138 police officers. Four officers who responded to the attack died by suicide within seven months. As of July 7, 2022, monetary damages caused by attackers exceed $2.7 million.

Called to action by Trump, thousands of his supporters gathered in Washington, D.C., on January 5 and 6 to support his false claim that the 2020 election had been "stolen by emboldened radical-left Democrats" and to demand that Vice President Mike Pence and the Congress reject Biden's victory

An automated teller machine (ATM) is an electronic telecommunications device that enables customers of financial institutions to perform financial transactions, such as cash withdrawals, deposits, funds transfers, balance inquiries or account information inquiries, at any time and without the need for direct interaction with bank staff.

ATMs are known by a variety of names, including automatic teller machine (ATM) in the United States (sometimes redundantly as "ATM machine"). In Canada, the term automated banking machine (ABM) is also used, although ATM is also very commonly used in Canada, with many Canadian organizations using ATM over ABM. In British English, the terms cashpoint, cash machine and hole in the wall are most widely used. Other terms include any time money, cashline, tyme machine, cash dispenser, cash corner, bankomat, or bancomat. ATMs that are not operated by a financial institution are known as "white-label" ATMs.

Using an ATM, customers can access their bank deposit or credit accounts in order to make a variety of financial transactions, most notably cash withdrawals and balance checking, as well as transferring credit to and from mobile phones. ATMs can also be

If your gas water heater is not working, first check to see if:

 - Is the water heater leaking? If so, turn off the water and gas to the heater, and contact a plumber to replace the heater.

If the pilot light does not light or continues to go out after heating the water, the thermal coupling on the water heater likely needs to be replaced. Contact a plumber to have this replaced.

In processes used in the manufacture of semiconductors, thin film transistors, solar panels, computer memory chips, and the like, volatile organic solvents are used to clean and process the substrates on which the semiconductor devices are formed. These substrates are typically made of silicon, although other materials may be used. The semiconductor devices are created when the substrates are coated with a thin layer of a material, such as amorphous silicon, that is then heated to a sufficiently high temperature, such as 600° C. or greater, to cause the silicon to form a crystalline structure, creating the semiconductor devices. The mass of the substrate is then cut into individual semiconductor elements, such as semiconductor dice or chips, and each of these individual semiconductor elements is then packaged in a plastic or ceramic package, such as a plastic flip chip, ceramic PGA, or a ceramic dual in-line package.

Linux, computer operating system created in the early 1990s by Finnish software engineer Linus Torvalds and the Free Software Foundation (FSF).

While still a student at the University of Helsinki, Torvalds started developing Linux to create a system similar to MINIX, a UNIX operating system. In 1991 he released version 0.02; Version 1.0 of the Linux kernel, the core of the operating system, was released in 1994. About the same time, American software developer Richard Stallman and the FSF made efforts to create an open-source UNIX-like operating system called GNU. In contrast to Torvalds, Stallman and the FSF started by creating utilities for the operating system first. These utilities were then added to the Linux kernel to create a complete system called GNU/Linux, or, less precisely, just Linux.

output:
-

I have long thought that there is no good reason to believe in the existence of a god, or gods, any more than to believe in the existence of an omnipotent god. That is, I would like to understand the concept of god in and of itself, and not as a wishful omen for a perfect life, or a moral compass for human action.

How is a non-existant thing like a god better than a non-existing thing like a god?

I would like to understand the concept of god in and of itself, and not as a wishful omen for a perfect life, or a moral compass for human action.

Personally I find the concept of a supreme being to be an extremely useful tool in understanding the nature of the universe and our place within it. If it is indeed the case that such a being does not exist, then what harm can it do to believe that such a being does exist?

The only harm I can see is that people like theists believe in a god which they cannot prove exists. If the theist cannot prove that a god exists, then the theist cannot be sure that a god exists and must make the best case he can for the existence of a god.

One of the major problems with the theist's case for god is that the theist has to assume that god exists. I'm guessing that non-theists think that we don't need to assume that god exists.

The second major problem with the theist's case for god is that, by the theist's own admission, no *direct* evidence exists in support of the theist's case for god. The theist must instead rely on indirect evidence. Unfortunately, the indirect evidence that the theist can rely on is so incomplete and so contradictory that it is impossible to make any kind of case for the existence of god.

In other words, the theist's case for god rests on theory, not on evidence.

label: Assuming god exists, one can think of the nature of god in two dimensions: is god active or passive, and is god benevolent or indifferent? Therefore, god is either active and benevolent, active and indifferent, passive and benevolent, or passive and indifferent. If god is active and benevolent, then all the bad things that happen would not happen, so this combination is unlikely. If god is active, god would likely be benevolent, so an indifferent active god seems a low probability. If god is benevolent, one would think they would be active, so a benevolent passive god seems a remote possibility. That leaves as the likeliest scenario a god that is passive and indifferent.

Powers of the press

By Brendan Conway

IT’S BEEN a busy couple of weeks for the media. A spate of scandals has engulfed the big players, while the newspapers have gone to great lengths to protect their own.

These events have made the front pages, but the best stories have been the ones not in the papers at all.

Papers have been forced to cover court cases involving police misconduct, the leaking of documents and the resignation of a judge.

The stories are compelling. But they don’t sell papers.

This is why the media have to be very selective about the stories they choose to run. It’s like being a taxi driver, picking which passengers you’ll take to the airport.

The media often get stories wrong. Stories about the tax rate, for example.

This newspaper recently carried a story on a tax cut that would cost the average worker £500 a year.

We got it wrong. The story had the headline “I’ll pay more tax, says ‘average worker’”, while the article was actually about the owner of a furniture shop.

The media place a huge amount of emphasis on the fact that the average income tax rate in the UK is 40 per cent.

In fact, it’s the richest 10 per cent of households that currently pay almost half the tax.

This is a central plank in the argument for tax cuts. The government wants to cut the burden of tax on the poor.

In fact, the rich get a lower tax rate than the poor.

The media’s obsession with the tax rate ignores the fact that the richest one per cent of families pay more than half of the income tax.

And the media love to run stories about the rich people who don’t pay any tax.

But it’s the stories about the poor that sell newspapers.

Age and genetics

The majority of people fall somewhere in the middle.

There are some people who are naturally fast runners. They can run for hours and miles and never get tired.

They don’t need to train at all. In fact, they may tend to run too much because they’re unable to take a break.

There are other runners who are naturally slow. They never get tired and they train for hours and hours but they never get any faster. They just keep improving their times over time.

Introduction of the Greenhouse Effect

One of the most common misconceptions about global warming is that the Earth is heating up because of the excess amount of heat energy being absorbed by the atmosphere. The idea that the Earth is getting hotter and hotter is wrong, because the Earth is not getting hotter, it is getting cooler!

In a great article on the greenhouse effect, you will learn about the different ways in which the Earth is being cooled down, and you will find out why greenhouse activity is responsible for the cooling down of Earth’s surface.

The greenhouse effect

The greenhouse effect is the natural phenomenon in which the Earth’s atmosphere is acting as an insulator. The Earth’s atmosphere protects the surface of the Earth from the harshness of the outer space.

The Earth’s atmosphere is like a blanket that covers the Earth and keeps the surface of the Earth warm. The Earth’s atmosphere acts to trap the heat energy that is emitted from the surface of the Earth.

If there was no greenhouse effect, then the Earth’s surface would be like a furnace that would emit as much heat as it can, and the surface temperature of the Earth would increase, which would be very dangerous.

The Earth’s atmosphere acts as a blanket that keeps the Earth’s surface cool and warm, and the surface temperature of the Earth would not change.

The greenhouse effect is responsible for the Earth’s atmosphere retaining heat energy and preventing the surface temperature of the Earth from rising.

Types of greenhouse effect

There are two types of greenhouse effect:

1. Direct greenhouse effect

It is the natural phenomenon in which the Earth’s surface is being cooled by the greenhouse effect.

The direct greenhouse effect is the process by which the Earth’s surface is being cooled by greenhouse gases.

2. Indirect greenhouse effect

It is the natural phenomenon in which the Earth’s surface is being kept cool by the greenhouse effect.

The indirect greenhouse effect is a process by which the Earth’s surface is being kept cool by the reflection of light from the Earth’s atmosphere.

Charlotte’s Web by E. B. White

Charlotte’s Web by E.B. White is one of my favorite books. I know it’s not a very popular book, but I think it deserves to be. I don’t think I have ever read or heard a bad review about this book. In fact, I never read or heard anyone talk about not liking this book. I look at it as one of the classic books in children’s literature. It is the book that every child should read at least once in their lives.

Charlotte is a spider who has lost her silk producing ability. She’s been living in her barn all her life. Her life is filled with taking care of her mother and father spiders, eating the flies that bother them and doing all the chores like cleaning out the barn, keeping the mice out, and so on. All the while, the barn has been getting smaller and smaller since the flies have kept coming to eat her mother and father’s silks. One day, a veterinarian comes to see her mother and father’s webs and tells her that they’ll soon die, and that she has to move out of the barn. She takes the webs and goes to live with her aunt and uncle. Her aunt tells her that she has to earn her keep. Her aunt and uncle are farmers, so she has to do all the chores, like feeding the chickens, cleaning the barn and doing all the other farm chores. That is the beginning of a lot of hard work. In the end, the farmer has to move out of the barn, and Charlotte has to take care of the chickens, the barn and all the other farm chores.

This is a wonderful book. It makes you think. You don’t get these types of books anymore. I loved it. I wish I could read it to my children.

Are there different types of transmissions?

There are two types of transmissions, manual transmission and automatic transmission.

What is a manual transmission?

A manual transmission gearbox is a gearbox with a manual control lever. The gearbox has one set of gears, which drives the wheels. The gearbox is controlled by the driver by engaging the gears or by disengaging the gears.

What is an automatic transmission?

An automatic transmission is a gearbox that automatically changes gears without the need of the driver to engage the gears. The gearbox is controlled by the computer, which senses the speed and torque of the vehicle and automatically changes gears accordingly.

An electronic transmission is a gearbox that is electronically controlled and automatically changes gears without the need of the driver to engage the gears.

AWD is a system that without driver intervention, shifts power between the rear and front wheels. This system is typically found on light-duty SUVs or passenger cars. The AWD drive system is designed for mild inclement weather conditions such as light snow, ice and rain. It is not designed for off-roading or severe weather conditions such as heavy snow or mud. This is where the 4WD system comes into the picture. 

4WD is a system that includes a transfer case that directly applies power to the rear axle, both front and rear axles and in some cases, only to the front axle. In addition, some 4WD systems include lower gear ratio options, locking hubs and lockers in the axles that force an equal amount of power to each wheel. All this taken together enables a 4WD system to enable a vehicle to navigate through deep snow, mud, over rocks and other obstacles with ease. The 4WD system is most commonly found on trucks, Jeeps and other purpose-built vehicles designed for heavy-duty use, whether for work or pleasure.

input: What are the most important tools to own when I am an apartment renter?
output:
.org/blog/how-to-own-your-apartment-rent-control

How to own your apartment

I found this video on Housebecomes website to be the most useful tool I’ve come across so far.

One of the first things I did after moving into my apartment was to get a copy of the property deed, as in the United States land deeds are usually public records. Before I could do anything with that document, I had to find a notary public. Once I was able to find a notary public that was willing to work with me, I was able to get that deed notarized and copy into the renters name.

The next thing I did was go to the county clerk’s office and have the document recorded.

The last step was to go to the city clerk’s office and have the city sign off on the deed. I had to go to every city clerk’s office I lived in to get this done, but I am happy to say I did it.

Once I had my lease signed by the city, I was able to take a copy of the lease, notarize it and file it with the county clerk.

I also needed a copy of the lease. I also needed to get the building manager’s signature on the lease and make sure the lease is in good standing.

The last step is to go to the county clerk’s office and have the county record the lease. It’s important to note here that some counties will charge you a fee to record the document.

I also want to mention that in some cases, you might want to have a notarized copy of the lease before you upload it to the county clerk’s office, in that case you will need to get that notarized copy from the county clerk’s office as well.

Now that I have my lease recorded, I am ready to start renting out my apartment.

IgD myeloma is the second most common type of myeloma. The objective of this study was to identify the clinical features of adult IgD myeloma patients. We retrospectively reviewed the medical records of patients diagnosed with IgD myeloma from 2000 to 2008. The patients were divided into two groups: those with hyperdiploid karyotype and those with non-hyperdiploid karyotype. The clinical features of the groups were compared. There were 26 patients with IgD myeloma, including 17 patients with hyperdiploid karyotype and 9 patients with non-hyperdiploid karyotype. The groups did not differ in terms of age, gender, and the presence of renal impairment or anemia. The hyperdiploid group was more likely to present with gastrointestinal symptoms (p=0.047), whereas the non-hyperdiploid group had a higher incidence of fatigue (p=0.002). The hyperdiploid group had a lower platelet count (p=0.041) and higher serum lactate dehydrogenase (p=0.008) than the non-hyperdiploid group. The incidence of lytic bone lesions did not differ between the groups (p=1.000). IgD myeloma is a disease that can present with varying clinical features, depending on the karyotype. Patients with hyperdiploid karyotype are more likely to have gastrointestinal symptoms. Patients with non-hyperdiploid karyotype tend to present with fatigue.Blabbermouth.net -

Delta Lake, Arkansas, United States

Delta Lake is a reservoir in the Ouachita National Forest of the Ozarks in north central Arkansas. It is in Howard County, about 50 miles northeast of Little Rock and 55 miles southwest of Fayetteville. It is located about 5 miles east of the Mississippi River, the second largest freshwater stream in Arkansas.

The lake is named after the Ouachita River, which flows into the lake at the north end of the lake, and which is formed by the confluence of the Ouachita and Little Ouachita rivers.

The lake covers 5,000 acres at an elevation of about 1,300 feet (400 m) above sea level.

The lake is managed by the Arkansas Game and Fish Commission as a wilderness area and a primitive area for fishing.

The lake is a popular place for fishing and boating, and has two boat ramps.

The lake has a maximum depth of 125 feet (40 m).

Autocross Events

There are many traits that great baseball and softball batters share.  Some of the most important are extreme confidence, sound batting mechanics, and coordination developed though a combination of talent and practice.  

All great hitters share some consistencies in their batting mechanics such as their lower half mechanics, their hand and bat path, and their head and eye movement.

With their lower half mechanics they generate powerful torque from the ground up by timing the planting their feet in a balanced position and forcefully rotating and opening their hips.  Hitting powerful line drives relies heavily on the barrel of the bat meeting the ball flush.  Batters increase the odds of this by keeping their hands in, connected to the back shoulder, and having one palm facing up and one palm facing down for as long as possible as the bat path travels through the strike zone.  Finally, all great hitters maintain consistent head and eye position throughout the motion. 

There are many nuances of batting mechanics that all great hitters share but these are some of the most important.

input: What are some criticism of Betty Friedan's Feminine Mystique?
output:
A:

Not much, other than that the book is a tract.  "Feminine mystique" is a phrase that Friedan coined.  It is a buzzphrase, like "The Pill", "sexual liberation" or "the personal is political".  It is not a term that's well-understood, and certainly not by the average non-academic reader.  
Friedan was a creative writer, and her book is a creative piece.  It's not a dry academic paper, but it is a book.  I'd say the book is problematic, but its author is not.  It's a problem for the reader, not for Betty Friedan.

A:

There are many criticisms of the book. The most obvious is the use of the word "Mystique" in the title. There is nothing mystical about the word, and it is a poor choice of word.
Another criticism is that there is little to no discussion of the problems the book actually addresses. It is primarily a celebration of the sexual liberation of the American woman, without any discussion of the feelings of the women who had become accustomed to the sexual repression of the past. This was addressed in the 1970s when the book was first published, but Friedan treated the issue as an afterthought in the original book. The book grew into a Bible of sorts for the women's movement, but was not well-received by women who had been through the sexual revolution.
There are also criticisms of the book, which you may read in the Wikipedia article.

A:

The Feminine Mystique is widely regarded as one of the most influential books of the 20th century. It has been the subject of countless scholarly studies and critiques, and continues to be a source of inspiration to many.
Yet, just a few years after its publication, Betty Friedan was rejected by her psychoanalyst, who concluded that she was psychotic from the stress of the publishing process. This was a severe blow to Friedan's self-confidence and led to a period of intense depression.
Despite the initial rejection, Friedan's influence on the women's movement has been profound. Many activists credit the book with opening their eyes to the many problems within feminism.

Scythris stellata

label: While groundbreaking, Betty Friedman took a narrow view on what the experience of a women is. She mainly focused on middle class white women. This narrow view meant she missed some of the challenges that women of other classes and races. As an example she focuses on the desire of women wanting to work without thinking about poorer women who are forced to work.

input: What is email?
output:
is email. It's how you send messages between computers that have a common protocol that is readable to the recipient. So, for example, an email server in California will be able to read an email sent from an email server in Germany.

Until roughly 10 years ago, email was a primary method of communication between businesses. Email made it easy to exchange documents and to communicate quickly and easily with people in other parts of the world.

The problem is that email is only one part of the infrastructure of the modern corporation. Email is only part of one piece of the communication puzzle: the other is instant messaging.

Messaging is the exchange of messages between two or more people using a messaging application. Messaging applications are real-time communications tools that are as common as email, and, like email, they are used for almost every kind of business communication.

The difference between email and instant messaging is that email is not real-time. Each time you send an email, the message sits in its queue, waiting for you to read it or for a recipient to read it. In contrast, instant messaging apps are real-time. Instead of reading the messages in your inbox, you can simply start a conversation.

But the real problem with email is not that it's not real-time. The problem is that it's not secure. If you send your company's confidential information to an email address, that email address, anyone in the world, can read that information.

As you can imagine, this was a problem well before the advent of social media. But social media has exacerbated the problem by making it easy to post confidential information to social media.

Just as email is the primary method of communication for many companies, instant messaging is the primary method of communication for many companies. But like email, instant messaging has many drawbacks.

Instant messaging applications are not secure

Because instant messaging apps are real-time communication tools, they are not, strictly speaking, secure communications tools. The apps do not encrypt the messages. In fact, they often do not encrypt the communications at all. Instead, they encrypt only the media — the actual text of the communication — which means that anyone in the world who comes across the email or instant message can read your communications.

This is an extremely serious problem, because the communications are not encrypted. This means that if your company's communications are intercepted, your company's communications can be read.

Because of this, instant messaging has become

input: How did George II die
output:
to elite.

He had a strong constitution and, in spite of his illness, he took to his bed but his condition worsened in the late summer and early autumn of 1751. The king's physician, Dr. Thomas Willis, was summoned to his bedside and he prescribed a regimen of vigorous exercise to help improve his circulation and thus the circulation of the blood. This did not help so he prescribed a diet of buttermilk, beef, and oatmeal; he also had to give up alcohol. The king was also offered grapes, baked apples, ginger, and turnips. A physician friend of the king, Dr. William Smellie, wrote:

> To the king about this time I mentioned that I thought his constitution was much deranged by the use of spirits, and he desired me to tell him what could be done in the case. I told him, that I thought if he took every grain of the sacred grapes he would find the dropsy would soon be done. He asked me what quantity of the grapes I thought he should eat. I told him that I thought he should eat the whole of the first crop of grapes. He seemed to be pleased with my advice, and said he would endeavour to follow it.

This was a typical case of the hot-cold disease. The king's condition worsened and he began to have difficulty breathing. On November 5, 1751, he was taken to London and put on a different regimen that consisted of more than buttermilk, beef, and oatmeal. He was also given more fruits and vegetables. Dr. Willis had given up alcohol but on December 15 George II began to drink a cup of wine and brandy and a small amount of cordial every day. On December 21 he was well again and was sent back to St. James's.

The king suffered a relapse in December, but he recovered. When he was well again, he cabled his brother, the Prince of Wales, that he was "not to be gambled with but be most careful of your health and you will be most welcome to me." He was visited by his old friend, the Duke of Hamilton. He wrote on his visit:

> He was very weak and had a low fever, and a pain in the right side of his stomach; but was still cheerful. He was very glad to see me, and I am very glad to have had an opportunity of seeing him, and he was pleased to say that
label: Fell off toilet

output:

The results are striking. French manufacturers dominate, with Lexus and Alfa Romeo among the top five. German manufacturers are the second-largest group, followed by American, Japanese, and other. The leading French manufacturer in first-time buyers is Lexus, with Hyundai second. Other car makers are well down the list.

One reason might be that the French are more likely to have bought a second car in the last three years, but the differences between the countries are not purely due to this. There are also differences in consumer culture, and in the car-buying mentality. The French tend to be more optimistic about their future and attitudes to money are more positive. This, in turn, leads to more car purchases in France than elsewhere.

The differences in consumer culture are also important, because they mean car companies can target different consumers in different countries. They can do this in two ways. First, they can give their products different names and identities. For example, in Britain, Audi and VW tend to be favoured by young, trendy buyers. Conversely, in France, Citroen and Peugeot are favoured by more conservative, older buyers. In Japan, Toyota and Honda tend to be favoured by the more affluent, while Nissan and Lexus are favoured by the less well-off.

Second, car companies can target different kinds of buyers. In France, Lexus is a favourite of 'gentleman drivers', a label the brand has tried to shake off in recent years. The brand has made a concerted effort to attract younger buyers, including a well-publicised ad campaign for its new JX models.

In Germany, Volkswagen is the brand of choice for the young, trendy, and well-off. Its 'people carrier' is the successful Golf. In Britain, Ford has been a key brand for young people who don't want to be tied down to a family car.

In America, Cadillac is the flagship brand, while Nissan is the 'people carrier'.

The British get a car for the family. The Japanese get one for the wife. The French get one for the husband. The Germans get one for the wife. The Americans get one for the wife and the husband.

affecting or affecting to a degree: The ordeal affected her so deeply that she could not speak.

adj.

having much affectation: a friend of the family with whom one has little in common.

made or done with affectation: an attempt to be funny with affectation.

having or showing a particular kind of effect: an affectation of humor.

having or showing an effect; effective: an affectation of simplicity.

adj.

serving to influence or excite feeling: an affectation of grief.

having or showing an emotional or aesthetic attitude: an affectation of indifference.

having a particular character or stamp: an affectation of arrogance.

marked by or exhibiting affectation or theatricality.

having a certain dramatic effect: The play is full of affectation.

brought to bear on or upon: The effect of the sun upon the plant life.

[Obs.]

produced by or as a result of the action of a drug or other agent: the effect of morphine.

anthropology. I am a historian of the early modern Atlantic world, but my
research and teaching interests include anthropological theory, and
historical methodology, especially the relationship between theory and
methodology. I am also interested in cultural history and the history of
European science.

I received my B.A. from Princeton University (2002) and my M.A. and
Ph.D. from the New School for Social Research (Syracuse University)
(2008).

I have been an Assistant Professor and a Visiting Assistant Professor

I have also been a Postdoctoral Fellow at the National University of
Singapore (2007-2009).

I have an extended family of professional genealogists, and I love finding
the stories of my ancestors and my extended family. I have published one
book (available on Amazon.com)
and have several articles in print and online (including journals and web
resources) on the history of genealogy. I also have a large collection
of handwritten family documents, photographs, and books, and I regularly
update my blog on genealogy.

and culture of the Mediterranean and Mesoamerican regions.

daughters: Emily and Lydia.

David Oliver Siegmund (born November 15, 1941) is an American statistician who has worked extensively on sequential analysis.

Siegmund grew up in Webster Groves, Missouri. He received his baccalaureate degree, in mathematics, from Southern Methodist University in 1963, and a doctorate in statistics from Columbia University in 1966. His Ph.D. advisor was Herbert Robbins. After being an assistant and then a full professor at Columbia, he went to Stanford University in 1976, where he is currently a professor of statistics. 

He has served twice as the chair of Stanford's statistics department. He has also held visiting positions at Hebrew University of Jerusalem, the University of Zurich, the University of Oxford, and the University of Cambridge.

Water is a very good conductor of heat.

Inhibitory effect of orexin on the activity of rat mast cells and the secretion of histamine and leukotrienes.
Orexin, a neuropeptide composed of two peptides, orexin A (OXA) and orexin B (OXB), is a recently identified hypothalamic neurotransmitter. Orexin neurons project to sympathetic and parasympathetic preganglionic neurons in the brainstem and spinal cord. These preganglionic neurons transmit the signals to various types of peripheral and central neurons including those in the autonomic nervous system. To study the physiological role of orexin in mast cells, we examined the effect of orexin on the secretion of histamine and leukotrienes from rat mast cells. We found that orexin A and orexin B dose-dependently inhibited the release of both histamine and leukotrienes from rat peritoneal mast cells stimulated with compound 48/80. This inhibition was reversed by a selective orexin receptor 1 antagonist, SB334867. The inhibitory effect of orexin on the release of histamine and leukotrienes was associated with the degranulation of mast cells. In addition, the inhibition of the release of histamine and leukotrienes by orexin was attenuated by a selective orexin receptor 1 antagonist, SB334867, or an intracellular Ca(2+) chelator, BAPTA-AM, or a selective phospholipase C inhibitor, U73122. These data suggest that orexin inhibits the release of histamine and leukotrienes from rat mast cells through a mechanism involving both the intracellular Ca(2+) response and phospholipase C. The physiological significance of this finding is that orexin may play a role in the regulation of the immune system, especially in allergic diseases.Healthy Foods

input: What was Robert Metcalfe's impact on society?
output:
Robert Metcalfe was an influential scientist who founded the key research institute that helped to create the Internet. His work was a major milestone in the development of the Internet and the computer world as a whole.

Metcalfe was born in 1944 in Epsom, England. His father was a scientist, and Metcalfe grew up in a large home with many pets. He was a good student and went on to study at the University of Cambridge. In the summer of 1967 he met a young man named Douglas H. Clark, who was a graduate student in computer science. Clark had established a research group at the University of Manchester, and Metcalfe was interested in joining. He came to Manchester, but shortly thereafter transferred to the University of Edinburgh to continue his studies. In 1970, he and Clark co-founded the Xerox Palo Alto Research Center (PARC) in California.

PARC became a hotbed of research and development in computer science, and Metcalfe was a key figure in the success of the center. Metcalfe's work at PARC helped to create the Ethernet, the first software-defined computer network and the first user-friendly network interface for personal computers. Metcalfe also helped to develop the Ethernet's successor, the Internet.

In the early 1980s, Metcalfe left PARC and returned to England to found a consulting company called Logic Systems. He founded Metcalfe Systems in 1983 and later added a provision for computer networking. His company did a great deal of work for the British government, the National Health Service, and several other organizations.

Robert Metcalfe died of a heart attack in June of 2003. He was only 66 years old.

Metcalfe was also a strong supporter of free speech. He believed that all people should be free to say what they want without being criticized and that people should be able to pursue their own interests in life.

Metcalfe's most important contribution to society was in the realm of computer science. He helped created the Ethernet, a network protocol that allowed for the easy transfer of data between computers. He also helped to create the Internet, which revolutionized the world of information.

Robert Metcalfe's impact on society was immense. He worked to create the technology that made the Internet possible. He also helped to create a free and open society, where anyone can say or do anything without being criticized.

Shauraseni Prakrit was a Middle Indo-Aryan language and a Dramatic Prakrit. Shauraseni was the chief language used in drama in medieval northern India. Most of the material in this language originates from the 3rd to 10th centuries, though it was probably a spoken vernacular around the 2nd century BCE in the ancient state of Surasena. 

Among the Prakrits, Shauraseni is said to be the one most closely related to Classical Sanskrit in that it is derived from the Old Indian Indo-Aryan dialect of the Madhyadesa on which Classical Sanskrit was mainly based. Its descendants include the languages of the Hindi Belt, the Central Zone of modern Indo-Aryan or Hindi languages, the standard registers of the Hindustani language based on the Delhi dialect.

input: Why are gaming conferences fun for everyone?
output:
.com

Wednesday, March 12, 2014

Gaming Retrospective: 2011

This is a retrospective of sorts, about the gaming industry in general and the year 2011 in particular. I'm doing this retrospective because I feel it is a good time to look back and evaluate 2011 from a different perspective.

E3

I remember very little about E3 2011. I was so excited for Halo 4 that I couldn't pay attention to the other games, which was unfortunate. Maybe I'll do a Halo 4 retrospective later. I remember the Nintendo presentation, though. I don't remember how much I enjoyed it, but I did remember how much I enjoyed the trailer for Super Smash Bros. for Wii U. I was also seriously impressed by the Wii U hardware.

This post isn't about what I liked about E3, though. It's about what I didn't like about E3. It was the greatest gaming show ever, in my opinion, but the show lacked the goodwill that I have come to expect from E3. I think the show had a lot of hype and a lot of value, but I think they forgot to do the most important thing: communicate.

The only thing that I remember from E3 were the trailers for games like Forza Horizon, Assassin's Creed IV, and The Last of Us. The lack of communication was frustrating, because I never knew what to expect from E3 in the first place. I would have preferred being surprised by the trailer for the new Bioshock, but even that would have been better than being surprised by nothing. It would have been nice to see some new ideas from the big N, instead of just the same games they've been peddling for years. It would have been nice to see some games that I have never heard of before.

Forza Horizon and Assassin's Creed IV were the most disappointing surprises. Forza Horizon is a great racing game, but I was expecting a new Forza Horizon game. input: What medicinal plants should I grow in my Mid-Atlantic garden?
output:
January 10, 2013

Dear Annie:

It's good to see that your garden is suffering from the cold, though it sounds like you are making the best of things! I am growing some "hardy" medicinal plants, as are many of my neighbors, but I have noticed that it is getting harder to find them.

I'm growing some of the same plants you are because I am determined to have a full, healthy garden this year, and I want my plants to be able to withstand the winter weather. Here are some of the plants I am growing that I am sure will be useful in treating your health problems.

• Catnip (Nepeta cataria) This is a perennial that produces a flowering spike-like shape that is covered with tiny purple flowers. The plant is used in tea for colds, coughs, and fever.

• Elder (Sambucus nigra) This is a shrubby plant that produces an attractive flower with three white petals that come out in the fall. The elder plant is also used in tea for coughs or colds.

• Ginger (Zingiber officinale) This plant produces a long stalk that looks like ginger root. Ginger is steam distilled to make a tea for digestive problems or to soothe a sore throat.

• Echinacea (Echinacea angustifolia and Echinacea purpurea) These two wonderful plants are native to the eastern United States. The plant produces a beautiful pink flower that is used in tea to help reduce colds and coughs.

• Goldenseal (Hydrastis canadensis) This is a plant that grows in the eastern United States and produces a beautiful yellow flower that is used in tea to help treat colds.

• Horehound (Marrubium vulgare) This is a lovely plant that is native to Europe and produces a lovely yellow flower that is used for tea to help loosen mucus in the throat.

• Motherwort (Leonurus cardiaca) This is a plant that grows in moist soil and produces a lovely yellow flower that is used in tea to help heartburn and as a diuretic.

• Osha (Ligustrum lucidum) This plant produces a beautiful yellow flower that is used in tea to help with colds and coughs.

• Peppermint (Mentha piperita)

Q:

Is it possible to create a mongodb query using an array of values?

I have the following collection:
{
    "_id" : "5f0ad001e7387701b9b4d1e4",
    "_class" : "com.mongodb.BasicDBObject",
    "__v" : 0,
    "name" : "apples",
    "quantity" : 2,
    "__v" : 0
}

I would like to query the collection using a query like this:
db.collection.find({"name": ["apples", "apples", "apples"]})

but this doesn't work. Is there a way to do this using a query?
This is the error I get when I attempt to execute this query:
> db.collection.find({"name": ["apples", "apples", "apples"]})
>
> Error: error: {
>     "$err" : "not authorized on apples.$cmd",
>     "code" : 13,
>     "errmsg" : "not authorized on apples.$cmd"
> }
>

A:

You can do it by using mongodb aggregation query.
db.collection.aggregate({
   $match: {name: 'apples'}});

or you can use below query for find:
db.collection.find({$or: [{name: 'apples'}, {name: 'apples'}, {name: 'apples'}]});

I find a lot of people talk a lot about who they like and don’t like. It’s like when you’re in high school and you want to impress someone, you say “I like this band, they’re awesome!” and try to convince the other person that you’re awesome too. When in reality you just like them because they’re popular.

I’m a big fan of Pearl Jam. Not extremely into the other bands, but the music is good.

Lately I’ve been listening to the Pearl Jam record Ten. I like it a lot, but I did find the first track “Daughter” to be a little boring.

@DaveyB I’ve never really listened to the other bands you mentioned (except maybe Soundgarden and Nirvana), I tend to stick to the “core” bands, but I like what you said about what people say about bands they like and not like. I use to do that a lot.

About to listen to the new album, the first track is “Daughter”, and its really good.

@DaveyB I also find that when people say they like a band, it’s usually because of how popular the band is, usually because of the commercial success (or lack thereof) of that band. I’m not saying that’s wrong, but I think it’s pretty hypocritical.

I’ve liked a lot of different music, but Pearl Jam is one of the few bands I’ve found that consistently gets me going. It’s not just good music, but good music that I can connect with. There are other bands that occasionally get me going, but not with near the frequency that Pearl Jam has.

I love Pearl Jam, but I’m not sure if they’re my favorite band. They’ve definitely been my favorite band for many years.
