Extensive intracerebral and intraventricular calcifications in a patient with pseudohypoparathyroidism.
We describe a patient with pseudohypoparathyroidism (PHP) who developed extensive intracerebral and intraventricular calcifications. The calcifications were not related to hypercalcemia. Serum calcium was slightly elevated, but the serum phosphorus was normal. The intracerebral calcifications were found in both the frontal lobes and in the cervical spinal cord, and the intraventricular calcifications were localized in both the lateral ventricles. These calcifications developed in the absence of vitamin D deficiency. The patient's serum PTH level was inappropriately low. The patient was treated with a low-dose calcium plus vitamin D3 preparation and with an active vitamin D3 preparation, but the calcifications did not regress. Although the calcifications were initially thought to be non-neoplastic, the patient subsequently developed progressive dementia. The cause of the dementia was uncertain but her mental status improved with hemodialysis, and she died from a cardiac arrest. This case suggests that the intracerebral calcifications and the intraventricular calcifications were not related to a high level of serum calcium, but that they may have been caused by a low-level of PTH.We are engaged in offering a wide assortment of Sash Window Stays. ?

The Committee on Philippine House is the executive committee of the House of Representatives of the Philippines, which is the lower house of the bicameral Philippine Congress. The committee was established on March 23, 1878, which was a measure of the Philippine Commission. The committee was used as the formal body to conduct the impeachment of President Manuel L. Quezon. The committee became a standing committee on May 1, 1939, and the bicameral Philippine Senate was established in 1947, which was a measure of the Commonwealth of the Philippines.

What is the committee's function?

The Committee on Philippine House is the principal body in the Philippine Congress for holding hearings and deliberations on matters related to Philippine legislation, amendments to Philippine laws and other matters pertaining to the Philippine Congress.

What is the committee's composition?

The Philippine House Committee is composed of the Speaker of the House of Representatives and the Majority Leader of the House of Representatives, who is a member of the committee, the Minority Leader of the House of Representatives and the Minority Leader of the House of Representatives, who are both members of the committee. The House Committee Chair is a member of the committee.

What is the committee's jurisdiction?

The committee's jurisdiction covers any of the following:

(1) Hears all cases of impeachment and removal of public officials, including the case of the impeachment of the President of the Philippines, cases of impeachment of the Vice President of the Philippines, the impeachment of the Secretary of the Department of the Interior and Local Government, the impeachment of the Secretary of Defense and the impeachment of the Secretary of Justice.

(2) Discharges its duties upon the resolution of the House of Representatives and the Senate of the Commonwealth of the Philippines.

What is the committee's functions?

(1) To initiate the impeachment trial and send the case to the Senate upon the resolution of the House of Representatives and the Senate of the Commonwealth of the Philippines.

input: What are the parts of a sail?
output:
a sail is made up of many parts. The most important of them are the hull (the body of the boat), the mast, the sail, the rudder, the deck, and the rigging (the ropes and lines that hold the sails to the mast and the boom). Here is a list of the parts of a sail.

The Hull

The hull is the body of the boat. It is made of many pieces that are sewn together. The pieces are called planking, frames, and stringers. It is important to make sure that the hull is strong and sturdy.

The Mast

The mast is the main part of the sail. It is a long, strong pole that is used to hold the sail in place. It is also used to hold the sail aloft. The mast is made up of many pieces of wood.

The Sail

The sail is the sailcloth that is attached to the mast. It is made of many pieces of cloth. The sail is the part of the boat that actually carries the boat through the water.

The Rudders

The rudder is a piece of wood that is attached to the bottom of the boat and points in the direction of the wind. It is used to steer the boat. It also helps to guide the water out of the boat's way.

The Rigging

The rigging is the ropes and lines that are used to hold the sails in place. It is also the rope that helps to keep the mast steady. It is attached to the mast and also to the boom.

The Deck

The deck is the part of the boat that is above the water. The deck is made of many pieces of wood.

enome.com

The Greek islands are best known for their gorgeous sunsets, beautiful beaches and relaxed attitude towards visitors. But Santorini is famous for another reason, and that is the volcanic eruption of Thera which happened around 3,600 BC. The blast was so powerful that it sent a tsunami across the Mediterranean destroying parts of Greece and Italy and leaving the island a pancake of rock, off the coast of Turkey.

The eruption is believed to have been caused by a large explosive event which flooded the caldera of the volcano with lava, ground up rocks and ash. Over the next few thousand years, volcanic activity within the caldera grew and grew until it became one of the most famous tourist spots in the world.

The eruption left a massive caldera and a number of smaller craters within the rim of the caldera.

The caldera is around 158km across and is composed mainly of obsidian which has cooled to a glassy consistency. The obsidian is made of shattered lava rocks and volcanic ash. A number of smaller craters then formed within the caldera, and the land above the caldera floor is now covered with lava flows and the remains of the smaller craters.

The most famous of the smaller craters is Akrotiri, which is now a UNESCO World Heritage Site. The Akrotiri crater was formed by a landslide which created a huge dome within the rim of the caldera. The dome then collapsed and collapsed on top of the caldera floor creating a large depression. The caldera floor is now filled with lava flows and ash, and the site of Akrotiri is now a large village located at the bottom of the caldera.

The aim of this study was to evaluate the prognostic value of the proliferation marker Ki-67 in patients with sentinel lymph node (SLN) metastases. The study included 225 patients with breast cancer and SLN involvement. The patients were divided into three groups: patients with no evidence of disease (NED), patients with micrometastases (M1) and patients with macrometastases (M2). The expression of Ki-67 and the number of SLN involved were correlated with the nodal status, tumor stage and axillary lymph node negative rate (LNR). The expression of Ki-67 in patients with M1 (7.8%) was significantly lower than in patients with M2 (41.7%) and NED (39.4%). shaira (also known as som, shaira bhuka and shaira-bhuja), is a mildly carbonated drink made from fresh or partially fermented tea leaves, water and sugar. It is typically consumed in the Indian subcontinent.

Contents

Tea contains polyphenols that are thought to aid in digestion. Shaira tea is an example of the use of these polyphenols in the body. The most common form of shaira is made with fresh or partially fermented tea leaves. The brown sugar is added to give the water a brown colour and to add a sweet taste. The tea is then infused with carbonated water to give it a foam and to carbonate the tea.

The most commonly used tea in these instances is Darjeeling tea, which has a long history of use in India. However, other teas can be used. Because the tea has been partially fermented, it has a less astringent taste and is less bitter than unfermented tea.

The drink is popular in India, Nepal and Pakistan and is also used in Sri Lanka, Bangladesh and Afghanistan. It is typically consumed with a piece of bread, a jaggery stick or a lime. The drink is also popular in Pakistan, where shaira is considered a national drink.

It is also used in Ceylon as an accompaniment to a meal. It is also used in the United Kingdom as a "tipple" or in other parts of the Commonwealth as a "bit of a drink". In the Arab world it is used in Kuwait and parts of the Persian Gulf. In Russia shaira is served in the form of a shot.

In the Indian sub-continent, shaira is served in the form of a shot. The shot is typically served over ice and is sold by vendors in the streets. The vendor will pour the shot into a glass and charge a small fee.

In the United States, shaira is a popular drink at parties and functions. It is typically served in a cup and sold by vendors in the streets. It is usually made with Darjeeling tea.

Shaira is also used as a flavoured drink. It is typically made with freshly-brewed tea and flavouring such as ginger, lime, and mango.

What is the history of Tax Day in the United States?

Tax Day, referred to as Taxation Day, is the day the U.S. federal government collects all taxes owed to it. Tax Day differs from calendar day in that it falls on the same day of the week every year.

Tax Day is celebrated on the last day of April. In the United States, April 15 is the day that all income taxes are due and payable, as well as any federal payroll and excise taxes. Some U.S. states extend Tax Day to the next day, and some states have no designated tax day.

The date of Tax Day in the United States is determined by Congress.

Although Tax Day is typically celebrated by Americans, it is also observed on the same day in some countries, such as Canada, Australia, and New Zealand.

Tax Day in the United States is closely tied to the tax return. Tax Day is not universally observed in all countries.

Because Tax Day is not universally observed, the date may be altered in some countries. For example, in Canada, Tax Day is celebrated on the second Monday in April. By contrast, European countries often celebrate Tax Day on the same day as April 15.

History of Tax Day

Tax Day is the day when the United States federal government collects all taxes owed to it. Tax Day is the day on which the federal government collects taxes owed to it by U.S. citizens and residents.

Tax Day was originally celebrated on April 15, 1792, by the Second Continental Congress. This date was chosen as the day of the year when the U.S. federal government would receive all taxes owed.

In 1789, the federal government was weak and had not received all of the revenue from the taxes it had levied. The Second Continental Congress established a tax levy in 1787, but the U.S. was still not able to collect all of the taxes owed at that time.

The Second Continental Congress also passed a law in 1789 to establish a date for determining the date of the federal tax levy and the date on which the U.S. federal government would collect taxes.

This law required that the U.S. federal government collect taxes on April 15 of each year. This date was chosen because it fell on a Monday, allowing the U.S. federal government to collect taxes in conjunction with the collection of federal payrolls and other federal taxes
label:
Tax Day exists as a deadline for many United States residents to report earnings in order to pay income taxes.

The United States introduced the income tax in 1861 in order to fund the American Civil War. This was later deemed unconstitutional and repealed in 1872. This was later reenacted in 1894 as part of the Revenue Act with its constitutionality settled in the Sixteenth Amendment to the Constitution in 1913. Tax day was initially set for March in 1913 and was eventually moved to April 15th in 1955.

The Bay Area is full of beautiful trails - and hiking is a great way to get a taste of the area. I've had the chance to visit many trails in the Bay Area, and I've found that there are five places that I always return to and recommend to others.

1. Alamere Falls

Alamere Falls. Photo by: Larry B.

Alamere Falls is one of the most spectacular places to hike in the Bay Area. The trail goes through a redwood forest, which is a short walk from the parking lot. The falls are a great place to take a rest and snap some photos. The trail is also beautiful and well marked. The falls are stunning; they are very tall and the water is amazing. It is very refreshing to cool off in the falls.

2. Redwood Regional Park

Redwood Regional Park. Photo by: Larry B.

This is another great place to hike in the Bay Area. The park is in the Redwood National Forest, and it is about a 25 minute drive from the Golden Gate Bridge. The hike is about 2 miles in length, and it is a moderate hike. It offers a great look at the majestic redwoods. The park has a great playground for kids too.

3. Stairway to Heaven

Stairway to Heaven. Photo by: Larry B.

Another great hike is the Stairway to Heaven. It is about a 15-minute drive from the Golden Gate Bridge. The hike is a moderate hike, and it takes you to the top of the hill. The trail is mostly flat, and you get some amazing views of the bay. The trail is pretty easy to follow, and it is a great place to take a break or snap some photos.

4. Stinson Beach

Stinson Beach. Photo by: Larry B.

This is another great place to hike in the Bay Area. It is about a 20 minute drive from the Golden Gate Bridge. The hike is a moderate hike, and it is about 2 miles long. It takes you to the top of the hill and you get a great view of the ocean. The trail is mostly flat, and the views are gorgeous. The trail is pretty easy to follow, and it is a great place to take a break or snap some photos.

5. Guided Hikes

The Sight and Sound of the 'Cat in the Hat'

House cats have about half the number of cones in their eye as humans, according to a new study. Researchers found that the color vision of house cats was like our vision for the first 400 nanometers of light -- but then it fell off sharply.

Cats are often thought of as "color blind," but their eyes are sensitive to a much wider range of colors than people's, according to the study in the journal Vision Research. Humans can see about 200 nanometers beyond the yellow-green end of the visible spectrum, but some species of cats, like feral cats, can see even shorter wavelengths, like the ultraviolet.

This ability to see ultraviolet light is important for hunting, because ultraviolet light can help cats spot the eyes of prey animals. But it could also be important for feline vision, according to the researchers.

"If cats are able to see ultraviolet light, they may be able to see other animals in the ultraviolet," said study author and neuroscientist Dr. Michael Dickinson of the University of Rochester. "So they may be able to see things that humans can't see."

For the study, researchers measured the cone cells in the eyes of two types of domestic cats: domestic shorthair, which is used for hunting, and domestic longhair, which is used for companionship. They also measured the cones in the eyes of eight other species of feline, including the cheetah and the lion. They found that the domestic shorthair had about half the number of cones that humans have in our eyes. The domestic longhair had about a quarter as many.

Cats were found to have about 30 percent of the cones that humans do. The other species of cats did not have enough cones for the researchers to test them, but they believe their cones are very similar to those of the house cats.

"I think it's fair to say that cat vision is pretty much similar to that of human vision," Dickinson said. But he said he wasn't sure how much the differences matter. "How much do the cones really contribute to what cats do, which is largely hunting or interacting with their owners?"

input: What is the boarding process at Southwest Airlines
output:
?

We are happy to answer any questions you may have about boarding process at Southwest Airlines. We make boarding a priority in all of our cities.

What is Southwest's boarding process?

When checking in for your flight, you will be asked to complete the boarding group screener. The group screener is a simple questionnaire designed to ensure that the group you are traveling with is safe and ready to depart the gate. You will be able to check in online or by phone and your ticket will be sent to you before you arrive at the airport.

What is the group size limit and how many people can board in one group?

On flights with more than 49 seats, the group size limit is 50 passengers.

Can I board early at Southwest if I have a small group?

Yes! You can board early at Southwest. Simply fill out the Request for Early Boarding Assistance form, or call the Southwest Airlines customer service desk.

What happens if I have a bag that cannot be checked in?

Check in your bag with the baggage check agent (or the airline's baggage service). If your bag cannot be checked in, fill out the Baggage Claim Form.

Is there an age limit for a child to fly alone?

Yes! You must be 21 years of age or older to fly alone on Southwest.

Can a child age 16 years old fly alone on a Southwest flight?

No, there is no age limit for a child to fly alone on Southwest.

Can I check in for a flight as an unaccompanied minor?

You must be at least 13 years of age to check in as an unaccompanied minor.

Will I be allowed to board the plane if my boarding pass has been lost or stolen?

You must present a valid boarding pass to be allowed to board the plane. If you do not have a valid boarding pass, you will be denied boarding.

What happens if my flight is delayed and I miss my connecting flight?

You may purchase additional tickets to make up the time you miss. Southwest will not make up the difference in fare.

Why is my reservation listed as "Reserved" on the flight status page?

If you check in for a flight, your reservation is reserved. If you check in for a flight, but the flight is overbooked, your reservation is not reserved. For detailed information on overbooking, please

input: What is a typical Humpback Whale migration pattern
output:
?
Humpback whales (Megaptera novaeangliae) migrate in the Southern Hemisphere's mid- to high-latitudes, with the majority (~80%) of their annual travels within the Antarctic Circumpolar Current (ACC). During the austral summer, adults and calves migrate primarily to the Antarctic Peninsula and subantarctic islands, where they feed on krill and other prey to fuel their long-distance travels. During the austral winter, they travel north into the tropical eastern Indian and Pacific Oceans. In some years, they move far north into the Arctic Ocean, but they are generally seen only in the Antarctic basin. The main migratory path is the so-called Antarctic humpback whale corridor (AHC), a region of relatively high productivity that extends from the Antarctic Peninsula to the Antarctic continent. The AHC is a relatively small area (~2,000 km2) compared to the size of the entire ocean basin (~16 million km2), but it contains a disproportionately large number of individual whales, a phenomenon known as the "humpback whale concentration effect." This effect is caused by the high average density of krill in the AHC and is due to the AHC being a region of high productivity, where krill are concentrated due to lack of competition from other prey species.

Humpback whales also migrate seasonally, and are thought to use a variety of pathways in the Southern Ocean. Some of these pathways are spatially distributed in a manner that can be explained by oceanographic features, such as eddies or meanders. Others have been named for their hypothesized use, including the "Southern Ocean Trail" (SOT) and the "Great Southern Ocean Route" (GSOR), both of which have been hypothesized to be used by humpback whales during their migration.

In general, the winter migration routes are less well known than the summer migrations, because many whales pass through the area under the cover of night. This makes it difficult to observe them in their natural environment, and many observations are made during the migration, rather than during the winter's rest.

Many questions remain about the humpback whale migration, including their migration patterns, how they use the AHC, and the reasons behind areas of high productivity in the AHC.

Where do humpback whales feed during their migration?
Although humpback whales are thought to feed on krill during their migration, it is difficult to prove
label: Humpback whales will typically feed in the summer months off the rich waters of Alaska, northern Canada and eastern Russia, and begin their migration to warmer waters of Hawaii or Mexico starting in mid-fall to breed.  The migration takes about 6 to 8 weeks and they begin arriving in Hawaii in late October/early November.  They will stay in warmer regions to breed and calve their babies during winter, and will start their migration back to the polar regions by late March or April.  It is estimated that up to 14,000 whales make this migration to Hawaii every winter.

It is also conventional to provide a seal between the shaft and the housing to prevent leakage of the rotor from the housing. One example of such a seal is disclosed in U.S. Pat. No. 3,705,377, which issued to B. L. Schmitt on Dec. 12, 1972.
The housing in prior art dynamoelectric machines typically comprises a cast metal alloy having a smooth cylindrical interior surface. The shaft extends through the housing and is secured to the rotor on one end and to the housing on the other end. The inner surface of the housing extends slightly above the outer surface of the shaft so that the shaft is spaced from the inner surface of the housing with a clearance which is on the order of magnitude of about 0.001 inch. The inner surface of the housing is typically not smooth or cylindrical, but has a plurality of ribs, slots, or the like, which serve to strengthen the material and to enhance the cooling of the housing.
The housing is secured to the shaft by a plurality of mounting plates, which are bolted to the housing. The mounting plates extend radially from the inner surface of the housing and are spaced circumferentially from each other. The mounting plates are secured to the shaft by nuts which are bolted to the mounting plates. The nuts are tightened against the inner surface of the housing to compress the mounting plates toward the inner surface of the housing. The mounting plates are thus secured to the shaft and the housing.
In order to assist in the tightening of the mounting plates against the inner surface of the housing, it is known to provide a seal between the shaft and the housing. A second seal is spaced from the inner surface of the housing and is secured to the housing. The first seal is compressed between the housing and the shaft to form a positive seal between the shaft and the housing. input: How to do forecasting with small dataset?
output:
:

A:

The simplest way to do this is to use a linear regression. You can find an introduction to linear regression in many places. The concept is that the dependent variable is the variable you want to predict, and the explanatory variable is the variable you want to use to make the prediction. For example, you could say that you want to predict the sales of a company, and you have several lines of data of sales of the company over time. Each time you have a data point for sales, you can use that to estimate the values of the dependent variable.
You can then add an intercept to the model, which is the value for the dependent variable if you start with no data. So, for example, if you start with no data for a particular company, then the dependent variable is sales. The intercept is then the value of sales for that company. This is essentially the average of the data points you have.
Once you have a model of this sort, where the dependent variable is sales and the explanatory variable is time, you can predict sales for a new time period by using the model. You can then get a forecast of sales for that time period by multiplying the predicted sales by the coefficient for time.

label:
Forecasting with small datasets can be challenging, as many traditional methods require larger amounts of data for accurate predictions.
Here are few approaches that can help you.

Simple moving average: This involves taking the average of a certain number of past data points, and using it as the forecast for the next period. This method can be effective for stable time series with no trend or seasonality.

Exponential smoothing: This method assigns exponentially decreasing weights to past observations, with more recent observations being given more weight. This method can be effective for time series with trend and/or seasonality.

ARIMA: The AutoRegressive Integrated Moving Average (ARIMA) model is a popular choice for time series forecasting. It can be effective for small datasets if the underlying data follows a pattern that can be modeled using an ARIMA model.

input: Why is Africa the least wealthy continent per capita?
output:
a

But a former deputy provost, who has been involved in the region’s politics for over a decade, said the G7 was “overly optimistic” about the effects of aid. “Aid has a huge multiplier effect, and that’s a fact that doesn’t get talked about enough,” he said. “The economics of aid is very, very important.”

The G7’s emphasis on debt relief is probably the right move, says Foster, because it will improve the countries’ economic prospects. “It would be very important for the credibility of the G7 to come out and say ‘we want debt relief, but we’re not going to solve climate change’. Debt relief is a very important element of that.”

But the G7 needs to deal with deeper problems. “The biggest issue in Africa is the political crisis. [The G7] is putting all its eggs in the aid basket. But if you don’t have things to say to the people in Africa, it’s not going to have the impact [the G7] think it will.”

The G7 should also be helping African countries to diversify their economies. “You need to get away from the reliance on aid,” says Foster. “If you look at China, for example, their economy has actually grown much more rapidly than the aid coming in. If you look at India, they’ve grown their economy at twice the rate as aid.

Foster thinks the G7’s focus on debt relief could be counterproductive. “If you can’t give debt relief, then [you need to] start giving them the money to develop the economy so they can generate income, so they can get their own development going.”

In fact, Foster thinks the biggest threat to the African continent comes from climate change, rather than corruption, which he says is still a problem in Africa. “If you look at the [climate] models, they’ve shown that the biggest impact on Africa will be the increase in sea level. The impact on people is going to be very much better for climate change than the impact from a corrupt regime.

“Africa is very rich, and it’s very poor. This is not an unsolvable problem. But if you look at it from the perspective of an African, it’s too early to say it’s unsolvable.”

Podcast | Who Is Your Persona?

»»» Subscribe to the Talking Business podcast:

We’re back with more Buzzwords. Today we’re talking about the identity crisis that is the internet and the struggle we’re having to figure out who we are and what we want to do with our lives. Does this platform give us the ability to be a completely different person each time we log on? Who is your persona?

Transcript

Cody: Hey everybody, welcome back to the Talking Business. My name is Cody Wallace and I’m your host.

Today, we’re talking about identity crisis. You know, a lot of times, I’ll do some networking events and you’re talking with somebody and before you know it, you’ve met them a lot. You’re drinking, you’re networking; you’re there and then you look at your watch and you’re like, “Oh man, I have to figure out what I’m doing next. I’ve got to get out of here.” Sometimes you have a lot of fun, sometimes you have a lot of business. But at the end of the day, you have to figure out what you’re doing and who you’re doing it for, right?

And sometimes, it gets confusing. You know, we’ve heard the term “persona” a lot. And in some ways, I think there’s a lot of misinterpretation around what this is.

So if you’ve ever been to a networking event, you know you’re wearing a suit. You’re wearing a tie. You’re wearing a nice shirt. You’re looking at your watch and you’re like, “Oh, I better get going. I’ve got to get out of here.” But the problem is, I’m guessing a lot of the people at that networking event, they’re wearing a suit and a tie. They’re wearing a nice shirt. They’re looking at their watch and they’re like “I better get going. I’ve got to get out of here.”

But if you asked them, “Hey, who are you? Why are you wearing this?” they’d probably tell you, “I’m a professional. I run a retail store. I’m a bank teller. I’

input: What is Credit scoring?
output:
credit score is the three-digit number that reflects your creditworthiness. It looks at your credit history, or credit report, to determine how likely you are to pay your bills. Higher numbers are considered to be better, and a low number is considered to be worse. According to the Fair Isaac Corporation, the most recognized credit scoring model, a credit score of 800 is considered to be the best score. The lower the score, the higher the risk that you’ll pay bills late or miss payments entirely.

What is a credit report?The most commonly used credit report is the Experian Credit Report. This report is based on information in your credit file. It is what lenders use to decide whether or not to approve you for a loan. This report includes your personal information, your credit history, and your credit score.

Credit scores range from 300 to 850. The higher your score is, the better your chances are to get a loan. If you have a credit score of 700 or above, you will have very good credit. However, if you have a score lower than 700, you may not have as many loan options.

How does a credit score affect your credit report?Your credit report represents a record of your credit history. Lenders look at how you have used credit in the past, and your credit history is used to calculate your credit score. Your credit score is used to determine your interest rates and your credit limits on loans.

Your credit score is based on how you have handled your credit in the past. If you’re consistently late paying your credit card bills, your credit score will decrease, and you may be denied a loan. You may also be charged more money, or have your interest rates doubled, if you have a low credit score. A low credit score can also make it difficult to get insurance, and may make it difficult to rent an apartment.

How is a credit score calculated?The formula for calculating credit scores is different for each of the three major credit bureaus (Experian, Equifax and TransUnion). These credit bureaus have different types of information. The credit bureaus may use information in your credit file or credit report. Data from the other two credit bureaus may also be used.

Data from one credit bureau may be used to calculate the score for another credit bureau. For example, if one of your credit card accounts is with a credit card company, the credit card company may send the credit bureau data on your account. This
label: This is a way of working out the risk of not being repaid if money is lent. Points are awarded for the answers given by the potential borrower to a series of questions. A high score means that the risk of them not being able to repay is low.

Learning objectives

After you complete this assignment, you will be able to:

• sum up the main events of Jalal Talabani's career as a political leader

• sketch a brief outline of the events of the Iraqi war

• describe the main events of the first years of the war.

Question 1

Jalal Talabani was born in the village of Saadoun on the Tigris River in northern Iraq in 1926. He was the son of a sheikh, who was a representative of the secondary tribal organization in the village. He followed his father's profession and became a sheikh too. As a young man, Talabani was active in the Iraqi national movement and was one of the founders of the Iraqi Communist Party. He also wrote for the Iraqi Communist newspaper, the al-Thawra.

In 1952, Talabani moved to Baghdad to pursue his career as a lawyer. He was a member of the Iraqi parliament for eleven consecutive years. During this time, he worked for the creation of a new constitution for Iraq and was instrumental in the first constitution of Iraq. He also worked for the independence of the Kurdish province of Iraq.

In 1963, he took part in the first coup d'état against the Iraqi monarchy. He was imprisoned for two years. In 1965, he was elected to the parliament as a member of the Arab Socialist Ba'ath Party. In 1969, he was elected the president of the Arab Socialist Ba'ath Party. In 1970, he was appointed President of Iraq. During his presidency, he was involved in the creation of the Ba'ath Party. He also worked for the independence of the Kurdish province of Iraq.

In 1979, he was appointed as the Prime Minister of Iraq. He won the election for the position and was later re-elected three times. In 1988, he was a candidate for the presidency of Iraq. He did not become the president, but he was re-elected as the Prime Minister of Iraq. He was involved in the establishment of a new democratic Iraq.

In 2003, he was the focal point of the Iraqi crisis. He was visiting Iraq and was kidnapped by the American troops. On 12 August 2003, he was released and went back to work in Iraq.

input: Netflix views streaming video as a "sustaining" technology that extends its core mail DVD business. Do you agree with this, or do you think streaming video is a "disruptive" technology for Netflix that does not align with its core business and requires a different strategy?
label: Netflix did a strategic renewal by cannibalizing its own cash cow business of mail-in-DVD services. This was the right move as internet speeds were increasing and moving towards broadband. Netflix was even considering launching a TV box if internet speeds remained constant. I agree that streaming video is a disruptive technology for Netflix, requiring a different strategy. Adopting a disruptive technology, Netflix forced Blockbuster to offer the mail-in-DVD service. By the time Blockbuster offered the mail-in-DVD service, Netflix had already begun experimenting with streaming videos and had started offering the streaming video platform. Netflix made Blockbuster dance to its tunes. Netflix, currently valued at $150 billion, changed its business model twice by cannibalizing its core services, shifting from mail-in- DVD service to subscription service to streaming video subscription service. This strategic renewal is one of the critical reasons for Netflix to become a valuable company and one of the pioneers

input: What is relational database
output:
?

A:

I think you may be confused by the term "relational database" which is used to refer to a particular database architecture - not the way the data are stored.
The relational model is a model of data and the database.  It is a model that has been around for a long time (since the early 1970's), and is used in a wide variety of applications.  What is different about the relational model is the way data are stored.  It is a common misconception to think that the relational model is a particular set of data storage techniques, but in fact this is not the case.  
In particular, the term "relational database" is often used to refer to a particular model of storage.  The database that is referred to by this term is a database that is based on a model of relations.  In general terms, a relation is a set of tuples.  A tuple is a set of items that are related to each other.  One common way to represent data in a relational database is to have each record in the database be made up of a set of tuples.  In this way, each record in the database can be thought of as a set of tuples - each tuple is a member of the record.
In general terms, a relation is any set of tuples that satisfies certain properties.  Common properties of relations include:

Each tuple is a member of some relation
Some "given set" of tuples is a member of some relation

The relational model is used to model the way data are stored by adopting a model of relations.  All the data are stored in the database in the format of a set of tuples that is a member of some relation.  This model of storage is based on a model of relations - not on a model of data.

A:

A relational database stores data in relation to each other, like tables in a database.

YARN is a distributed resource scheduler, which allows you to run applications on multiple machines simultaneously. YARN works on top of the MapReduce framework and allows you to run an application across multiple machines. YARN was originally developed by Yahoo! for their MapReduce framework.

How do I install YARN?

To install YARN, you will need to install several dependencies first. You can download and install all of the dependencies with the following command:

$ sudo yum install -y java-1.6.0-openjdk-devel

Once the dependencies have been installed, you can install YARN with the following command:

$ sudo yum install hadoop

Once YARN is installed, you will need to set a configuration file to point to your cluster.

$ hadoop-env

This will output the configuration file that you will need to modify.

$ cat /etc/hadoop/mapred-site.xml

This will output the configuration file that you will need to modify.

What is the difference between Hadoop and YARN?

While Hadoop is the framework that is used to run a MapReduce job, YARN is the framework that is used to run a MapReduce job on multiple machines.

It is important to note that Hadoop and YARN are not related to Hadoop, the programming language.

What is the difference between YARN and MapReduce?

YARN is a framework that allows multiple MapReduce tasks to run simultaneously on multiple machines.

What is the difference between YARN and Hadoop?

Hadoop and YARN are different frameworks in that Hadoop is the programming language while YARN is the framework that is used to run a MapReduce job on multiple machines.

How do I start a MapReduce job?

To start a MapReduce job, you will need to run the command hadoop-mapred-daemon. This command will start a MapReduce daemon on a given machine to process your MapReduce job.

How do I stop a MapReduce job?

The competition aims to promote the use of print dictionaries in undergraduate classrooms and to encourage student participation in the dictionary-making process. The competition is open to colleges and universities in the United States and Canada.

Entries must be in the English language and meet the following requirements:

Entries must be in a form that will allow them to easily be reproduced as a print dictionary. Entries should be submitted as a PDF file.

Entries must include a short synopsis, a list of keywords and definitions, and a brief explanation of the way in which the entry is intended to be used.

Entries must be accompanied by a synopsis of the author’s research and the methodology employed. The synopsis should be no more than one page in length.

Entries must include a page with a brief description of the author’s research and the methodology employed, and a page with appropriate citations.

Entries should not be submitted as a single PDF file. Entries should be submitted as separate PDF files: one for the entry itself, one for the synopsis, and one for the bibliography and citation. Entries should be accompanied by a letter of submission, which should be a one-page letter signed by the author and the author’s academic advisor or a faculty member of the institution to which the entry is submitted. Perez v. Campbell, 402 U.S. 637 (1971), was a case in which the Supreme Court of the United States held that Arizona's law suspending a driver's license was unconstitutional due to its conflict with the federal Bankruptcy Act under the Supremacy Clause of the Constitution.

The plaintiffs, Mr. Adolfo and Mrs. Emma Perez, were licensed uninsured motorists in the state of Arizona. Insurance was not required under Arizona law. Mr. Perez was involved in a traffic accident and, unable to pay the associated costs, soon filed for bankruptcy. Arizona, under its financial responsibility laws, withdrew the Perez' licenses, and the couple filed suit in district court, where their claim was denied. The Perez family's appeal to the United States Court of Appeals for the Ninth Circuit was denied, and they subsequently appealed to the United States Supreme Court, which granted certiorari.

photosynthesis

(hā`pəsī`səns), process of the conversion of light energy into chemical energy in green plants and algae. The process is carried out by specialized cells called chloroplasts, which contain the chlorophyll and other pigments. It is part of the life processes of the plant and animal kingdoms; in the plant kingdom it occurs mainly in the cotyledons of seeds and in the leaves of mature plants.

Chloroplasts contain chlorophyll, the green pigment in plants that is responsible for the green color. The chloroplasts are surrounded by a membrane that is selectively permeable to carbon dioxide, and they contain small amounts of other pigments that are involved in the process of photosynthesis. The reactions that take place in chloroplasts are as follows:

Electrons are transferred from water to the chlorophyll, which contains a pair of electrons in its base, forming a chlorophyll molecule with a positive charge. The electrons are passed to other chlorophyll molecules to form a series of iron-containing compounds called protochlorophylls. The iron-containing compounds are called protochlorophylls because they are formed before the chlorophylls. Protochlorophylls are available to the carbon dioxide formed by the oxidation of water by the chlorophyll. The carbon dioxide is combined with the protochlorophyll in the chloroplast to form chlorophyllide.

The chlorophyllide has a double bond in its structure, and the carbon dioxide is bound more strongly in its nucleus. The chlorophyllide is changed in the chloroplast by the action of ribulose bisphosphate carboxylase, which is a special enzyme that is part of the process of photosynthesis. The hydrogen atoms of carbon dioxide are added to the carbon atoms of ribulose bisphosphate carboxylase, forming the compound ribulose bisphosphate.

The double bond of the chlorophyllide is then reduced by NADPH, an enzyme that is also part of the process of photosynthesis. A series of reactions takes place, beginning with the formation of a compound called sedoheptulose bisphosphate. This compound is important in the process of photosynthesis. Another compound, glyceraldehyde 3-phosphate, is formed from sedoheptulose bisphosphate. The latter compound is important in the process by which the energy of the light is transmitted to the plant. The glyceraldehyde 3-phosphate is converted into the compound glyceraldehyde 3-phosphate. This compound is converted into the compound py

Okay kids, listen up. Nuclear fission is a very cool concept that gives us nuclear energy to power our homes and cities! You know how everything around us is made of little components called atoms, right? The centers of these atoms, called the nuclei, are themselves made of particles, called protons and neutrons. These particles are super tiny, hundreds of times smaller than the atoms themselves! Anyway, the particles in the nucleus are stuck firmly together, but if disturbed by a high-energy particle, the nucleus can split apart. When it does that, it releases a lot of energy as light and heat. This splitting of the nucleus is called fission.

In some materials, each nucleus that splits also releases more loose particles, typically neutrons, that can hit other atoms, and this leads to what's called a chain reaction: one atom splitting can cause others to do so, and keep releasing more energy. The four national languages of Switzerland are German, French, Italian, and Romansh. German, French, and Italian maintain equal status as official languages at the national level within the Federal Administration of the Swiss Confederation, while Romansh is used in dealings with people who speak it. Latin is occasionally used in some formal contexts, particularly to denote the country (Confederatio Helvetica).

In 2020, 62.3% of the population of Switzerland were native speakers of German (either Swiss German or Standard German) at home; 22.8% French (mostly Swiss French, but including some Franco-Provençal dialects); 8% Italian (mostly Swiss Italian, but including Lombard); and 0.5% Romansh.

The German region (Deutschschweiz) is roughly in the east, north, and centre; the French part (la Romandie) in the west; and the Italian area (Svizzera italiana) in the south. There remains a small Romansh-speaking native population in Grisons in the east. The cantons of Fribourg, Bern, and Valais are officially bilingual; Grisons is officially trilingual.
